<br>
If you can secure this spot solo, do it. With brand new earth pet after having turned 44, I let it loose on this guy. I breezed through the whole level in about 7 hours, and so far have gotten 1.33 bubbles into 45 in 6 hours. You might find other places that are better xp, but the word here is LOOT! Typical &quot;giant&quot; loot, which in Gornit's case works out to about 20pp PER corpse, and he spawns every 6 minutes. I've spent a lot of time so far on him, so I know my numbers are correct. I've made about 2500pp from just him, in a dozen or so hours. No more worrying about paying 20pp per scroll for practicing research.<br>
<br>
The strategy is not elaborate: you make an earth pet, give it swords of rune, Burnout II and a damage shield, and send it in. Two nukes of Shock of Swords and if necessary (keep checking pet's hp in comparison to Gornit's) another Blaze, or if things get resisted too much for no good reason (he has no MR to speak of but fully resists the odd nuke every now and then), just go all out nuking. My guess is he has around 2300-2500 hp.<br>
<br>
Keep trying new pets until you have one that hits for 46. It's worth it.<br>
<br>
If you're one looking for variety (and who isn't when soloing), try this: Buff yourself with Arch Shielding and Phantom Plate. At the same time you give your pet a DS, give yourself one as well. Don't send in the pet, rather nuke Gornit with SoS right off the bat. Let him hit you, which alerts the pet to chime in and start rooting. When root sticks, move out of his range and then switch on auto-attack and move closer until you start hitting (those focus items have quite a long range). Gornit is a &quot;dumb&quot; mob and will keep hitting your pet as long as it's closer to him than you are. Move in every now and then to actually get hit, because the whole reason for this strategy is that when your DS hits a mob, it counts as Offense and increases the skill. If you're a real masochist, just go right to his feet and take a beating until you are at 2 bubbles health. Troughout all this meleeing, you have to nuke with SoS at least once, or your pet just isn't gonna make it. With the buffs you have on yourself, you can regen to full health in time to do this on every second Gornit.<br>
<br>
DON'T LAUGH. I got my Offense skill from 85 to 109, and Defense up several points, in about 10-12 hours of camping him. And my 1H Blunt is up from 20 to 27! Like I said, it breaks the monotony of soloing a single spawn. What if the epic weapon is 1H Blunt and has a decent ratio like 15/30? I want to be able to wield it in combat if I get it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  But I have lots of work to do to make up for neglecting melee for 40 levels...<br>
<br>
As is usual with mega-loot mobs, throw out silver and copper (in excess of 150 of each per corpse, on occasion). If you don't have a weight reducing bag, I suggest throwing out the Fine Steel he drops, because it will weigh you down way too much. I'm lucky, I have Evil Eye Bag and Light Burlap Sack, so I could hold out very long before having to go sell to the high elf merchant in the tower on AC island. Every 4 hours or so, the sheer amount of platinum and gold coins weighs me down so much that I have to gate to Freeport to dump it all in the bank (and marvel at my earnings). Damn this guy has good loot.<br>
<br>
Gornit's level is mid to high thirties. He can hit for max of 88/90/92/94/96. His lowest form should be blue until 46 at least, and his highest to 50.<br>
<br>
On top of all that, he gives Firiona Vie faction... for those that need it.<br>
<br>
Can you beat the sheer LOOT on this guy (200pp per hour) at this level?<br>
